units.fr_title: Kafr Takharim Salqin - 60km west of Aleppo - 14 October 2012
units.summary_en:
Syrian government airstrike on Kafr Takharim or Salqin in Idlib (or between the neighboring villages) contained a toxic substance that was soft and light, like cotton or spiderwebs. Mosques made public announcements from minarets warning residents not to touch the white substance in the streets.
Based on time of social media posts, the attack occurred around 12:30 Syria time on 13 Oct 2012.

units.summary_en:
Syrian government forces launched an attack with chemical weapons on al Khalidiya or al Bayada in Homs (or between the two neighborhoods). One report indicated the chemical weapon was a nerve agent. Numerous people were injured and brought to a small medical facility for treatment. Many patients suffering from choking and difficulty breathing were treated with oxygen masks, and some patients had their partially clothes removed, which is consistent with treatment for exposure to a chemical weapon. Local sources reported about eight individuals were killed in the attack, by exposure to the chemical weapon.
First tweets reporting the attack were posted around 17:45 Syria time on 23 Dec 2012.

units.summary_en:
Pro-Syrian government sources accused opposition forces of firing a missle laden with chemical weapons on Khan al Asal, a town southwest of Aleppo city. SANA reported that the missile fell in a civilian-populated area, about 300 meters from a military location. Pro-government sources and government officials reported 25-31 people were killed in the attack, and 85-110 people were injured, including civilians, children, and soldiers. Russian officials backed up the Syrian government's claims and condemned the attack. SANA also published pictures of people allegedly injured in the attack, receiving treatment in a medical facility.
Alternatively, pro-opposition sources accused Syrian government forces of launching a chemical weapon attack on Khan al Asal. Pro-opposition sources included little details on the the effects of the attack or casualties.
First tweets about the attack appeared at 9:40am Syria time on 19 March 2013.

units.fr_title: Al-Otaiba - 30 km east of Damascus - 19 March 2013
units.summary_en:
Syrian government forces launched a chemical attack on al Oteiba on March 19, causing casualties. Victims of the attack, some of whom exibited difficulty breathing, were treated with oxygen masks in a medical facility. At least one patient exibited foaming at the mouth and significant difficulty breathing. Another patient was treated with an IV. At least one person reportedly died from the attack. All patients seen receiving treatment in the medical facility (about five in total) are young men.
First tweets reporting the incident were posted at 8:45am Syria time on 19 March 2013.

units.summary_en:
Syrian government forces reportedly attacked Adra, Damascus with weapons containing chemical agents. Medical workers clad in protective gas masks and gowns treated patients in medical facility in nearby Douma, Damascus. Many patients were treated with oxygen masks and displayed difficulty breathing. Many patients had their clothes partially removed, and some were washed down with water. A few patients displayed pinpoint pupils, which is a symptom consistent with exposure to a nerve agent. Another patient was foaming at the mouth, which is also consistent with exposure to a nerve agent. A few patients appear to have mild traumatic injuries but most appear to be suffering from non-trauma related injuries. The medical facility is overwhelmed with patients and treating victims on the floor. All patients seen in vidoes are young men.
First social media posts reporting the incident were posted around 10:00pm on 23 May 2013.

About a dozen videos show people - many young men, but also at least two babies, a child, and a woman - being treated with oxygen masks in a medical facility. Many of the victims have their clothes [artially removed. Many patients are being treated on the floor of the medical facility because there are not enough beds. One victim appears to have pinpoint pupils and tremors in his fingers, both of which are symptoms of exposure to a nerve agent. Al Arabiya reported six people were killed and more than 70 were injured in the attack.
First social media posts reporting the attack appeared around 11:00pm Syria time on 26 May 2013.

Syrian government forces launched an aerial assault on the Jobar region of Northeast Damascus. Airstrikes and artillery attacks caused severe damage and destruction to buildings within the region. Reporters from "Le Monde" explained their findings concerning the toxic arms used by the Syrain government. It has been reported that the chemical attack is hard to detect. "
No odor, no smoke, not even a whistle to indicate the release of a toxic gas. And then the symptoms appear. The men cough violently. Their eyes burn, their pupils shrink, their vision blurs. Soon they experience difficulty breathing, sometimes in the extreme; they begin to vomit or lose consciousness." http://www.lemonde.fr/proche-orient/article/2013/05/27/chemical-war-in-syria_3417708_3218.html

units.summary_en:
Syrian government forces reportedly launched an attack with chlorine gas on Kafr Zita in Hama on 22 May 2014. A video shows a dense mustard-colored gas settled close to the ground on a street lined with small buildings, around dusk or dawn. Men wearing gas masks run towards the gas to assist people running away from the gas while covering their mouths. Additional videos show alleged victims of the attack, most of whom are women and children, receiving treatment in a crowded medical facility. Many patients are coughing and are treated with oxygen masks and IVs. A medical worker treating a small girl says in English that the patients were exposed to toxic chlorine, which was dropped in a bomb from a helicopter. The Hama Media Center reported 20 people were injured in the attack.
There were multiple reports of chemical weapon attacks on Kafr Zita in the days leading up to 22 May 2014.
The first reports of this chlorine attack appeared around 12:15pm Syria time on 22 May 2014. Given the timing of these reports and the lack of sunlight in the videos, the attack likely occurred around dawn, which was at 5:24am on 22 May 2014.

units.summary_en: On September 24th, 2014 in the town of Adra, Damascus, chemical attacks were reportedly used in Adra. Based on two videos that link to this attack (https://cube.syrianarchive.org/littlefork/youtube_video/862725144d01924b24a466d7941c072e559f05ad5b6e51cc727f08e0f8e7aff4/y7eP5hOuvTA.mp4) and (https://cube.syrianarchive.org/videoapiresults/ShaamNetwork_S.N.N/dM9eqdCEwBY%D8%B4%D8%A7%D9%85%20%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%81%20%D8%AF%D9%85%D8%B4%D9%82%20%D8%B9%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7%20%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AA%20%D8%A7%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%A7%D9%82%20%D8%AC%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A1%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%B5%D9%81%20%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%BA%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%AA%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%A9%2024%209%202014%20%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B0%D9%8A%D8%B1%20%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%AF%D9%8A%D9%88%20%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%8A%20%D8%AC%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%8B.mp4), the videos show that many civillians as well as militant fighters were attacker and were aither injured or who had been killed by the chemical attack. The first video shows multiple elderly men who were brutally attack with the chemical weapon and in the second video linked showed certain fighters in the Battle of Adra that were injured or who were killed by these chemical attacks. The french intelligence reports (https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/IMG/pdf/170425_-_national_evaluation_annex_-_anglais_cle81722e.pdf) that people who were exposed to these attacks had symptoms of breathing diffiuclties and convulsions. Syrian state media have claimed that they had taken over the city (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2RA0lVhvB3U) and media reports from Al jazeera (http://www.aljazeera.net/news/reportsandinterviews/2014/9/29/%D8%A8%D8%B9%D8%AF-%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D8%B7%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84%D8%A9-%D8%B9%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%B8%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A) and the LA times (http://www.latimes.com/world/middleeast/la-fg-syria-adra-20140925-story.html) report that the syrian military brutally took over the town of Adra and in the LA times report, they stated that the rebel forces have claimed that when the Syrian military took over the town they had used posionous gas likely chlorine gas to recapture the city of Adra.

units.summary_en: On November 3rd, 2014 in the town of Talbiseh, Homs, chemical weapons were reportedly dropped in Talbiseh as well as brutal bombardment of the city throughout the battle between the opposition and government forces. According to this article (http://www.watanserb.com/archive1/2014/11/06/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%87%D9%88%D8%B3-%D9%82%D8%AA%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B7%D9%81%D8%A7%D9%84/) many children and families were brutally killed under contant bombardment and military raids from the Syrian regime. They link the source from the Syrian observatory that 22 had been killed and 16 members of a family were killed in the military raids. Videos of the post chemical weapons attack in Talbiseh was provided by Shaam news (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bfSMHPzrx10&feature=youtu.be&has_verified=1), this video shows an elderly man who had been injured in an airstrike and this video (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mPnZfUXxUhI&has_verified=1) shows a little girl who had been paralyzed and extermely injured from the air raids as well in Talbiseh. The last video provided by Al Shaam shows a man who was killed in an airstrike (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NUHhuY3vuFU&feature=youtu.be&list=UUHk32FBOnL8E7ehkDfGMh4Q&has_verified=1). Furthermore, an article published by Al Arabiya reported on the massacre that the Assad regime had allegedly committed in Talbiseh (https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/arab-and-world/syria/2014/11/04/%D8%B3%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%A7-%D9%86%D8%B8%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%AF-%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%AA%D9%83%D8%A8-%D9%85%D8%AC%D8%B2%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%AC%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AA%D9%84%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%A9.html), they report that suspected rockets carrying chlorine gas was used in attacking the town which injured and killed kids, elderly people, and innocent civillians.

units.summary_en: Near the end of February of 2015, in the town Nawa which is located in the city Daraa, there were reports of indiscrimante barrel bombs being used in rebel-held town which have mainly hurt innocent civillians. According to the human rights watch report (https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/02/24/syria-new-spate-barrel-bomb-attacks) they analyzed since February of 2014, cities such as Daraa have been consistely bombarded with barrel bombs and continued to February 2015. The human rights watch report also noted new barrel bombs that hit specific towns in Daraa, they state according to the Violations Documentation Center that 609 civilian deaths, including 203 children and 117 women, in Daraa from aerial attacks between February 22, 2014, and February 19, 2015. Many of the casualties of these barrel bombings were innocent civillians, and many of these documentation is relied from human rights groups either based in Syria or outside of Syria.

units.summary_en: The location of the chemical attack was in Al-Janudiyah, Syria which is in northern Syria specifically in the Idlib Governence on May 7th, 2015. According to media articles from the Times of Israel (https://www.timesofisrael.com/syrian-activists-report-new-chlorine-attacks-in-idlib/), ibtimes, newsweek, and human rights watch they reported that provinces in Idlib throughout the battle held in the Northwestern Syria province, chemical attacks had occured and to add the geopolitical element to these attacks, many of these attacks according to Al Jazeera, between the months of April-June 2015, the Assad regime has continously bombarded rebel held areas to weaken their offense and while at the same time, has used chemical weapons in different provinces in the city of Jisr al-Shugour which included, Al-Janudiyah, Al-Bashiriya, and Al-Sarmaniya. These attacks occured around the same days in the month of May 2015 in the city of Jisr al-Shughour. The chemicals were put into multiple barrel bombs that were dropped in multiple villages as mentioned in the beginning. According to the article published by the Times of Israel, 80 people were injured in the attacks which included children who were killed as well as elderly Syrians. Many of the images and documents that conclude these reports were mentioned in the articles by human rights activits on the ground which included images of the weapon and destruction of the cities. Overall, we can infer that the chemical weapons attack was lanuched allegeldly by the Syrian regime throughout the battle between the rebels and government forces in Idilib.

units.summary_en: According to the Human Rights Watch https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/13/syria-coordinated-chemical-attacks-aleppo and Bellingcat https://www.bellingcat.com/news/mena/2016/12/19/the-cl2-before-the-storm/ on 18 November 2016 between 8 and 9 am, government helicopters dropped 5 barrel bombs containing chlorine on the districts of Masaken Hanano and Ard al-Hamra in Eastern Aleppo. The Aleppo Civil Defense recorded that 12 people were injured by the attack, including an old woman and several children. Witnesses recall smelling chlorine moments after the bombs were dropped, and reported seeing yellow smoke rising from the areas of the attack. A video posted by Orient News shows some of the injured in a makeshift hospital receiving treatment [dc29bc28]. Another video posted by the AMC shows remnants of a yellow cylinder barrel bomb dropped during the attack [f67c19bc]. Other videos posted by SMART and خاص الجسر show the destruction in the neighborhoods affected and include witness testimonies [3b8cec5f] and [8f17471f].

units.summary_en: On 25 November 2016, the Sheikh Maqsoud district, populated mainly by Kurds, was reportedly shelled by Islamic opposition groups at 19:12. According to ARA News, the attack was carried out by Ahrar al-Sham and Jabhat Fateh al-Sham, killing 6 individuals and injuring 15 https://web.archive.org/web/20170418081739/http://aranews.net/2016/11/syrian-islamists-launch-chemical-attack-on-kurdish-district-in-aleppo/. Victims reportedly suffered from suffocation, burning skin, and vomiting, which are symptoms that coincide to the exposure of mustard gas. A video on the Syrian Archive shows a victim receiving treatment in a makeshift hospital.

According to ARA News, the attack was carried out by Ahrar al-Sham and Jabhat Fateh al-Sham, killing 6 individuals and injuring 15 https://web.archive.org/web/20170418081739/http://aranews.net/2016/11/syrian-islamists-launch-chemical-attack-on-kurdish-district-in-aleppo/. Victims reportedly suffered from suffocation, burning skin, and vomiting, which are symptoms that coincide to the exposure of mustard gas. A video on the Syrian Archive shows a victim receiving treatment in a makeshift hospital.  SHE251116 2016-11-25

units.summary_en: According to the Human Rights Watch https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/13/syria-coordinated-chemical-attacks-aleppo, on 28 November 2016 the Aleppo Media Center and Shah News Agency reported about chlorine attacks on Karam al-Qaterji and Qadi Askar. Munitions dropped on a playground in a public park. Firas Badawi, a photographer with the AMC who witnessed the incident, noted that there was yellow-green smoke and a strong smell of chlorine. Around 11 to 12 people were injured and experienced symptoms of difficulty breathing, a loss of consciousness, pain in their chests, coughing, burning in the eyes, and foaming from their mouths. Another 11 people were injured after the gas was carried with the wind, and two people possibly died during the attack. Another witness claims a helicopter dropped an object near a cemetery in Qadi Askar at 3pm and about 20 people were injured and transported to hospitals for treatment. We didn't find any visual documentation that verify this incident

units.summary_en: According to Human Rights Watch, between 4 and 5 pm on 8 December 2016, chlorine attacks on Kalaseh and Bustan al-Qasr were reported by the AMC and Shah News Agency https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/13/syria-coordinated-chemical-attacks-aleppo. HRW suggests that these claims refer to three chlorine munitions that struck al-Maghayer neighborhood in the Bab al-Maqam district, al-Fardous, and Kalaseh. A witness to the event claimed the first attack struck, followed by another strike close to al-Hayat medical clinic in Kalaseh. Around 50 people, including 20 children were injured and experienced shortness of breath, foam exerting from the mouth, dizziness, headaches, and drowsiness. Al-Hayat clinic took in 70 patients for treatment. One witness claims two people were killed in the attack. A post on facebook posted by ( Halab Today TV قناة حلب اليوم ) reported that : "Helicopters target Al-Kalasa district in besieged Aleppo with barrel bombs containing chlorine gas  " https://www.facebook.com/HalabTodayTV/photos/a.422583204425790.121836.353338088016969/1587982244552541/?type=3&theater. We didn't find any visual documentation that verify this incident

units.fr_title: Bustan Al-Qasr- Near Central Aleppo- 8 December 2016
units.summary_en: A city located in the Aleppo governate called Bustan Al-Qasr, a once rebel held area now controlled under the Syrian regime, the city had been bombarded with intesne force by the Syrian regime thousands of families were forced to leave from their homes. Bombings in Bustan Al-Qasr started on December 8th, 2016. The victims of the bombardment in Bustan included children, women, and in general many were inncocent civillans.  The purpose of the attack by the Syrian government was try to take over Aleppo to gain territorial control back to the Syrian government. Acorrding to a report from the New York Times (https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/09/world/middleeast/syria-aleppo-united-nations.html) , many had been imprisoned, tortured, and bodies lying on the street from constant bombardment by the regime. Furthermore, some of the innocent civillans throughout the conflict between the government and rebel forces had either reported that the rebels would prohibt civilains from leaving the city and some stated that they actually allowed civillians to flee. According to a report from the Gaurdian (https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2016/dec/13/eastern-aleppo-as-pro-assad-forces-move-in-in-pictures), they have documented multiple images of Syrians from Aleppo which includes the city of Bustan Al-Qasr, showing women and children fleeing from their homes due to constant clashes between the syrian and rebel forces. Thus, we can assume that the constant bombardment that was perputrated by the syrian regime has forced many to flee from their homes, displacing them and as to the reports that were mentioned, many innocent civillans were killed, imprisoned, tortured, etc. by the syrian forces.

units.summary_en: The location of this Massacre is Al-Firdous which is located in Aleppo. The continous bombardment and attacks from the Syrian regime started in early December 6th, 2016. There was also usage of chemical weapons by the syrian regime according to the human rights watch (https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/13/syria-coordinated-chemical-attacks-aleppo), the chemical weapons used were chlorine gas from the video provided by the Human Rights Watch. According to numerous reports specifically by Aljazeera (http://www.aljazeera.net/news/arabic/2016/12/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%B8%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%B5%D9%81-%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%AF%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%AD%D9%84%D8%A8), mass executions had been occuring in the town of Al-Firdous since December 6th 2016. Many bodies filled the streets from constant bombardment in which the town was besiged making it difficult for inccocent villians to flee from bombs falling from russian and syrian helicopters. The victims of the masacre were inncocent people that ranged from children, the elderly, women, also rebel fighters. Footage of the massacre is provided by the White Helmets ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5ghIjs2vFk0) as well as photograghs and more video footage by al jazeera (http://www.aljazeera.net/news/arabic/2016/12/12/%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D8%B8%D8%A7%D9%85-%D9%8A%D9%88%D8%A7%D8%B5%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%B5%D9%81-%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%82%D8%AF%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%AD%D9%84%D8%A8). The footage provided by the White helemts shows multiple bodies that are deaceased from shellings and with Al Jazerra's footage, many women were fleeing from Aleppo and the video captured the destruction caused by the shellings. Moreover, we can infer based on media collection of the massacre, video caught footage, and images of the destruction post-shelling that these attacks were allegedly perpeturated by the syrian regime and their allies which includes russia and hezzbollah. units.summary_en: The location of this chemical attack took place in Al-Kalasa located in the city of Aleppo. The chemical attack occured in December 9th 2016. According to a USSOM report (http://www.uossm.org/breaking_chemical_weapons_attack_in_kallaseh_aleppo), they concluded that reports of chemical attacks from the use of chlorine gas, a choking agent, were targeted on innocent civillians in Kalasa. The Human Rights Watch also reported chemical weapons attack in the town of Al-Kalasa on December 9th, 2016 (https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/13/syria-coordinated-chemical-attacks-aleppo). The report by USSOM, provided a google drive of three videos that provides more explicit information on the chemical attacks that took place. In all three of the videos provided, there were a few children who were injurded by the chlorine gas and getting care from the doctors as well as the women. The doctors were shown treating the children who were attacked by the chlorine gas as well for the elderly women shown in the video. In the human rights report, they showed images of continous chemical weapons that were used in cities around aleppo and these yellow cylinders were filled with chlorine gas which was the chemical used in the town of Al-Kalasa. Furthermore, we can infer that based on the evidence provided by the USSOM report of videos showing the after math of the attacks as well as the report from the Human Rights Watch that the syrian government was allegeldy behind the the chlorine attacks in Al-Kalasa. units.fr_title: Bustan Al-Qasr- Near Central Aleppo- 12th December 2016
units.summary_en: The city of Aleppo, Bustan Al-Qasr, there were reports of chemical weapons attack, the use of chlorine attacks allegdly by the Syrian government forces attacking the rebel-held areas. This took place on December 12th, 2016. According to a bellingcat report (https://www.bellingcat.com/news/mena/2016/12/19/the-cl2-before-the-storm/) , they uploaded photos and sources from medical centers in the city of Bustan Al-Qasr called, Bustan Al-Qsar Medical Center. They reported from those medical centers that many inoccent had been targeted; children, women, and genreally inncocent cilvillans in the city. The weapon as described by the bellingcat report and from a report from the Human Rights Watch (https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/13/syria-coordinated-chemical-attacks-aleppo) , the chlorine attack was dropped by gas cylinders filled with chlorine dropped from a helipcopter. The reports as mentioned, provided pictures of the children who were attacked, videos of the chemical weapons being dropped from helicopters and their aftermath of the bombs being dropped. Moreover, we can infer that these attacks were perputrated by the Syrian government in the previously rebel-held area of Bustan Al-Qsar which has injured and killed numerous inncocent civillains.

units.summary_en: On December 12th, 2016 a neighborhood in East Hama, Uqayribat, the district was attacked with chemical weapons that were dropped by war planes. According to the Human Rights Watch report (https://www.hrw.org/report/2017/05/01/death-chemicals/syrian-governments-widespread-and-systematic-use-chemical-weapons), they recieved information from the locals of the neighboorhood reporting that there were war planes dropping the chemical weapons and that ot was done by the syrian and russian regime. This neighboorhood had a strong ISIS hold as well so many of the locals stated that they weren't allowed to document the chemical attacks because of fear from the Islamic State. According to Al Arabi's report (https://www.alaraby.co.uk/politics/2016/12/12/%D9%82%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%88%D8%AD%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D8%AE%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%A8%D9%82%D8%B5%D9%81-%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3%D9%8A-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%B1%D9%8A%D9%81-%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B4%D8%B1%D9%82%D9%8A) they reported that many civillians in neighborhoods of East Hama suffucated because of the chemical weapons which were linked to be Sarin gas according to the media report. Going back to the Human Rights Watch report, 67 locals died from the chemical attacks and these were noted by medical charity workers on the ground, on ground activists, etc. Furthermore, reports by the Human rights watch and well established media reports collected on the chemical attack in Eastern Hama conclude that the attacks were allgedly done by the syrian and russian regime in order to combat the Islamic State that has a strong hold in eastern Hama even though many pf the attacks had harmed numerous innocent civillians.

units.summary_en: On January 3rd, 2017, a town in the city of Damascus, Wadi Barada, it was reported by the new arab (https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/news/2017/1/5/poison-gas-used-in-regime-attacks-on-wadi-barada) that the syrian regime had deployed chemical weapons and had also cutt water supply of the town. That same week, on January 8th and 9th 2017, the syrian regime had deployed more chemical weapons, specifically chlorine gas. According to the Human Rights Report (https://www.hrw.org/sites/default/files/report_pdf/syria0517_web_3.pdf) they provided witness testimonies of the locals who lived in the village. Dozens of innocent civillans were injured or dead. Furthermore, based on the reports provided from the new arab and from the human rights watch, we can concluded that assads regime allegedly used chemical weaons on its own people in chances of winning the territory against the rebels.

units.summary_en: The Syrian regime bombed the city of Arbin in Rif Dimashq province in Damascus with chlorine gas on February 9, 2017, for the second time in less than a week. The city was also bombed with chlorine gas the next day. Human Rights Watch reported that three combatants were injured as a result of the attack. Bellingcat conducted a detailed investigation of the February 9 attack using local sources and cited one reported casualty. Qasioun News Agency reports that victims were transported to a hospital in Arbin, and a reporter interviewed a medical professional on staff. Video footage posted by local sources document victims at the hospital experiencing convulsions, difficulty breathing, and foaming at the mouth.

units.summary_en: Around 6:45am, a Sukhoi 22 aircraft, a warplane operated only by Syrian forces, dropped three conventional bombs and one chemical bomb in Khan Shayhoun in Idlib.  The UN Commission of Inquiry of Syria  reports that the chemical bomb, strongly presumed to contain sarin gas, killed at least 83 people including 23 women and 28 children, and injured another 293 people, of which 103 were children. Human Rights Watch reported 92 deaths and hundreds injured. Injuries comprise symptoms expected of exposure to sarin gas, such as breathing difficulties, loss of consciousness, foaming at the mouth, and irritation. Investigations by the Organization of the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons Fact-Finding Mission in Syria, Human Rights Watch, and Bellingcat, among other groups, have conducted separate investigations into the attack.

units.summary_en: One video from Ruptly shows an explosion near a water tower among many buildings. It appears to be filmed from a window. it then shows a rifle shooting from a window slit, but the target is not visible. It also shows machinery inside a building that is shooting out of what appears to be a slit. Due to lighting, neither the machinery nor the target are visible. Next, it shows a group of 6 armed men running through rubble. It returns to a shot of a rifle shooting towards buildings and rubble through what appears to be either a window or car with iron bars. It gives a snippet of a plane flying and then army men loading bombs, ending on an explosion behind a mound of dirt near a telephone tower. There is also a tweet stating "Faylaq al-Rahman reports regime chlorine use on the Ein Terma front, where the regime has recently had trouble in its advance attempts" from John Arterbury(https://twitter.com/JohnArterbury/status/881176064386617345). The Washington Post, among other sources, state the Syrian rebel group Faylaq al-Rahman accused the Syrian Army of using chlorine gas (30 people allegedly suffered from the attacks), while the Syrian Army denied vigorously.

units.summary_en: Multiple reports of government chlorine attacks on Faylaq al-Rahman fighters emerged in the first days of July amid ongoing clashes in the Ayn Tarma, Zamalka, and Jobar suburbs of Damascus. While there are no sources directly implicating a chlorine attack in Ayn Tarma on July 2, several sources depict the attack on the suburb on July 1 as noted in entry ETA010717. Faylaq al-Rahman released a statment on July 1 claiming their fighters were attacked with chlorine and released a video interview with a commander on July 4. The German Welt newsite published an article on July 22 citing western intelligence sources confirming a chlorine attack against Faylaq al-Rahman fighters in Ayn Terma on July 1.
